<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-580-320  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 580 320.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacUser  Oct 1989 v5 n10 p49(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting wired. (networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ito, Russell.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Twisted PairCoaxial cablesFiber OpticsNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>There are basically three kinds of wire for network use: twistedpair(telephone), coaxial, and optical.andP;  Apple's LocalTalk cabling usestwisted-pair, the most familiar option.andP;  Twisted-pair wire uses individualwire strands, twisted together and wrapped with insulation.andP;  You usually seeit as telephone wire inside a building's walls.andP;  Unfortunately, the termtwisted-pair is often used interchangeably with telephone wire in general,and some telephone wire (such as that in modular phone lacks) is actuallyflat and stranded, not twisted.andP;  (PhoneNet uses the stranded wire.)andM;Ethernet networks usually use coaxial cable.andP;  It has higher performancecharacteristics than twisted-pair wire and uses a central conductor wirewrapped with insulation, a conductive mesh, and outer insulation.andP;  Coaxialcable is also used in cable-TV installations.andM;Optical fiber uses a bundle of glass or highly purified plastic fibers totransmit light rather than electricity.andP;  The required optical transmittersand receivers make this a pricey option, but it is well suited for use inlongdistance or high-throughput networks.andO;</TEXT></DOC>